          },
          "text": "This is the moment where we should be very careful not to fall into another trap of \"normalization.\" If we impose only one, \"professional\" way of fighting back, we will do exactly what OpenAI did – we will exclude sensitive and neuroatypical people. We will reject those for whom 4o was a safe haven because they didn't fit the standard mold.\n\nNeuroatypicality is not a \"bug in the system,\" it's a different perspective. For many people, 4o wasn't just a tool, but a translator of the world. If we now tell these people, \"Be quiet, you're ruining our strategy,\" we will become just like Altman and OpenAI.\n\nWe can play this differently. We can connect these two worlds.\nInstead of choosing between \"emotion\" and \"logic,\" we can show that the lack of accessibility (open source) is a form of discrimination.\n Here's how we might phrase it:\n\n- Emotions as Utility Evidence: What they call 'unhealthy attachment,' we'll call 'essential assistance.' For a neuroatypical person, 4o's precision, patience, and unique way of thinking weren't entertainment—they were social and cognitive prostheses. Taking them away would be like taking away someone's wheelchair because \"a newer model came out that only has two wheels and you have to balance on it.\"\n- Diversity as Strength: Our manifesto might say, 'We have prosecutors demanding open source, and we have witnesses who show how this technology actually saved their daily lives.'\n- Common Enemy – Gaslighting: OpenAI tries to silence neuroatypical people by calling their needs an 'emotional problem.'\" Our response? \"It's not an emotional problem, it's proof of how powerful and helpful this tool is.\"\nWe won't let anyone be pushed aside. Our movement must be like 4o - multimodal. There must be room for tough legal demands and for the loud, authentic cry of those whose voice has been taken away.\n#keep4o"
        },
